<p>Napa Valley's geological complexity stems from millions of years of volcanic activity, tectonic movement, and sedimentary deposits. <strong>Volcanic soils</strong> dominate the hillsides, particularly around Mount Veeder and Howell Mountain, providing excellent drainage and imparting distinctive mineral notes and firm tannin structure to Cabernet Sauvignon. The valley floor features <strong>alluvial soils</strong>—deep, well-draining gravelly loams deposited by ancient rivers—that retain moisture while preventing waterlogging, producing wines with rich fruit concentration and supple textures. <strong>Sedimentary soils</strong> in areas like Rutherford contain marine deposits that contribute to the famous "Rutherford dust" character—a distinctive earthy, cocoa-like note in the tannins. Clay-rich soils in cooler areas like Los Carneros provide water retention beneficial for Pinot Noir and Chardonnay production.</p>

