<p>The valley's north-south orientation and varied elevations create distinct wine zones. Valley floor vineyards (200-400 feet) benefit from deeper soils and warmer temperatures, producing full-bodied wines with ripe fruit character. <strong>Hillside vineyards</strong> at 800-2,000 feet elevation experience greater temperature variation, UV exposure, and stress, yielding wines with more concentrated flavors, structured tannins, and enhanced aging potential. Eastern-facing slopes receive gentle morning sun, preserving acidity, while western exposures get intense afternoon heat, promoting phenolic ripeness.</p>

