<p>The <strong>Napa River</strong> creates humidity and temperature moderation, while the Mayacamas and Vaca mountain ranges provide protection from extreme weather. Most critically, marine fog from San Pablo Bay flows through the valley each evening, cooling the vines and extending the growing season. This fog influence is strongest in southern areas like Los Carneros and weakest in northern Calistoga, creating a natural temperature gradient. Areas with consistent fog penetration, such as Yountville and Oakville, produce wines with remarkable balance—ripe fruit flavors combined with refreshing acidity and elegant tannin structure, exemplifying Napa Valley's ability to achieve both power and finesse.</p>

