<div class="space-y-6">
  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What's the difference between Napa Valley Cabernet Sauvignon and Sonoma County Cabernet?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Napa Valley Cabernets typically show more power, concentration, and structured tannins due to the valley's warmer climate and well-drained volcanic soils. Sonoma County Cabernets often display more elegance and bright acidity, particularly those from cooler areas like Alexander Valley. Napa's iconic producers like Screaming Eagle and Harlan Estate exemplify the valley's bold, age-worthy style that commands premium prices.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Is Napa Valley wine good for beginners, or should I start elsewhere?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Napa Valley offers excellent entry points for beginners, particularly from established producers like Robert Mondavi, Beringer, or Cakebread Cellars who craft approachable, well-balanced wines. Start with Napa Valley Chardonnay or Merlot before progressing to the more tannic Cabernet Sauvignons. However, consider starting with less expensive Napa wines (under $50) to develop your palate before investing in premium bottlings.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Why are Napa Valley wines so expensive compared to other California regions?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Napa Valley's premium pricing stems from limited vineyard land (only 45,000 planted acres), astronomical real estate costs exceeding $500,000 per acre in prime locations, and the region's established global prestige. The valley's Mediterranean climate and diverse soil types consistently produce exceptional fruit, but small production volumes and high demand from collectors worldwide drive prices up significantly compared to larger regions like Central Valley.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What's the best way to store Napa Valley Cabernet Sauvignon for aging?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Napa Cabernet Sauvignon requires consistent temperatures between 55-65°F, 60-70% humidity, and protection from light and vibration to age properly. Most premium Napa Cabernets can age 10-20 years, with cult wines like Caymus Special Selection or Silver Oak developing complex tertiary flavors of leather, tobacco, and cedar. Store bottles on their sides to keep corks moist, and avoid temperature fluctuations that can cause premature oxidation.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Which Napa Valley sub-appellations offer the best value for money?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Calistoga and Pope Valley typically offer better value than prestigious areas like Oakville or Rutherford, producing excellent Cabernet Sauvignon and Zinfandel at lower price points. Mount Veeder and Atlas Peak, while producing outstanding wines, often cost less than valley floor appellations due to lower name recognition. Look for producers like Frank Family (Calistoga) or Bale Grist Mill (St. Helena) for quality wines under $75.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What's the biggest mistake people make when buying Napa Valley wine?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">The most common mistake is buying based solely on reputation or price without considering the wine's intended drinking window and your personal taste preferences. Many collectors purchase young, tannic Napa Cabernets without the patience or proper storage to age them properly, leading to disappointing experiences. Always check vintage recommendations and consider whether you prefer fruit-forward wines (drink young) or complex, evolved flavors (age 5-15 years).</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Are there good alternatives to expensive Napa Valley Cabernet under $50?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Yes, seek out Napa Valley producers' second labels like Penfolds Max's or Stag's Leap "Hands of Time," which offer similar winemaking philosophy at lower prices. Consider Napa's other varietals like Merlot, Petit Verdot, or Cabernet Franc, which deliver complexity without the Cabernet Sauvignon premium. Alternatively, explore neighboring regions like Sonoma's Knights Valley or Mendocino's Anderson Valley for similar climate and style at better value.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">When is the best time to visit Napa Valley wineries for wine purchases?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Visit during weekdays in spring (March-May) or fall (September-November) for the best tasting experiences and access to winemakers, avoiding the crowded summer tourist season. Many wineries offer library wines and exclusive bottlings only available at the tasting room, making direct purchases worthwhile. Harvest season (August-October) provides unique opportunities to purchase futures or limited-edition wines, though reservations are typically required well in advance.</p>
